details: Brown was fatally shot in the chest. His body was discovered in an abandoned house frequented by drug users. Ronald "Shorty" Mitchell, 45, was charged with second-degree murder in October. Prosecutors say the two men had argued and Mitchell left but returned and shot Brown. Mitchell was under the supervision of the state Department of Corrections at the time.

Young was with a friend when a gunman opened fire on them from a Cadillac, hitting Young in the head and chest. Anthony J. Smith, 17, was arrested hours later in SeaTac on unrelated firearm and drug charges. Smith, who was charged with first-degree murder in March, wanted to kill rival gang members as part of an ongoing feud between two gangs, prosecutors said.

Zavala, a student at Highline High School, was shot in the head in the parking lot of a Burien apartment complex. A car was seen speeding off and a group of people left the scene on foot. No one has been arrested in connection with Zavala‚Äôs death. Five days after his killing, a 36-year-old man was wounded in a shooting in the same parking lot.

Cross, a clerk at the Union Station Market, was stabbed to death when he grabbed the collar of a customer and tried to shove the man out of the store. During the altercation, David Allen Moore, 50, allegedly stabbed Cross at least three times. He was identified from DNA on a travel mug left behind in the store. Moore was charged with second-degree murder, with a deadly weapon enhancement.

Sippach was visiting Humphrey in Humphrey's apartment at Bell Tower, a Seattle Housing Authority building in Belltown. According to police, the bodies had been in the apartment for more than a few days before they were discovered. Both men died from multiple blunt-force injuries to the head. There have been no arrests.

Zapata and Tran were fatally shot and three other people were wounded in The Jungle homeless encampment during an apparent drug rip-off. The suspected shooters are brothers James and Jerome Taafulisia, now 18 and 17, who were charged as adults while their now-14-year-old brother was charged as a juvenile with two counts of second-degree murder and three counts of first-degree assault.

Hilts and two other men were shot at the Shell gas station on Rainier Avenue South, just north of South Othello Street. Hilts died at the scene; the other victims, ages 47 and 50, were hospitalized with serious injuries. Seattle police said at the time they believe the three men were targeted. There have not been any arrests.

According to prosecutors, Gennings was allegedly set up by a friend, Michael Rogers, now 17, to be robbed of marijuana and cash. Rogers‚Äô co-defendant, Diante Pellum, now 15, is accused of shooting Gennings once in the back of the head while Gennings sat in the driver‚Äôs seat of his car outside a Taco Bell restaurant. Both have been charged with first-degree murder and will be prosecuted as adults.

Demond Hudson, 27, and BJ Meaola Silipa, 26, took their dead 6-month-old boy to St. Francis Hospital in Federal Way, where hospital staff called police after finding the baby had suffered numerous injuries and appeared malnourished. An autopsy determined "DJ" had 21 rib fractures of varying ages, a newly broken right arm, a possible skull fracture and other injuries. In November, the parents were each charged with second-degree murder.

Fountain was stabbed to death when he tried to break up a fight between his mother and her boyfriend, Fritz Karl Ratcliffe, now 27, according to prosecutors. The couple had been dating for six months and Ratcliffe had moved in two months before Fountain was killed. Police say Ratcliffe fled but was arrested in Anacortes. He is charged with second-degree murder domestic violence.
Nickerson's body was found in the roadway. He moved to the Seattle area from Mississippi in 2013. No one has been arrested in his death.

Seattle police were conducting surveillance outside a suspected drug house when they saw Taylor, a known felon, arrive and spotted him wearing a holstered handgun. The officers called for backup and say he reached for a gun when they tried to take him into custody. He was shot by two officers and later died at Harborview Medical Center, where medical personnel found six ounces of crack and black-tar heroin in a bag around his neck.

Gondo's body was found slumped over the steering wheel of his car on Feb. 24, but the medical examiner‚Äôs office determined he had died a day earlier. Maryanne Atkins, then 16, is accused of shooting Gondo in the right temple with a gun Gondo kept under the front passenger seat. Atkins, who was charged as an adult with first-degree murder, allegedly killed Gondo to rob him of $3,000 cash.

Nesbitt was shopping at a QFC supermarket when Brandon Benevides is accused of violently shoving a grocery cart into him, causing him to fall and break a hip on Feb. 29. Prosecutors say the incident was unprovoked and part of a disturbing escalation in Benevides‚Äô erratic, violent behavior. Nesbitt died from complications of his injuries in April. Benevides, 34, was charged 10 days later with second-degree manslaughter.

Partman was on a sidewalk outside the Muckleshoot Casino when she was struck by an out-of-control SUV driven by Russell Duane Ward, 35. Ward was wanted on a Department of Corrections warrant and allegedly thought an Auburn patrol officer, who was responding to a burglary call, was trying to pull him over. Ward was charged with second-degree murder.

Blacktongue walked into a 7-Eleven and attacked a customer and clerk with a hatchet, according to the King County Sheriff‚Äôs Office. The customer, who had a concealed-pistol license, fatally shot Blacktongue. The clerk suffered a minor wound to the abdomen. In September, prosecutors declined to file charges, concluding the customer, a 60-year-old Seattle man, used lawful force in shooting Blacktongue and was defending the clerk from further injury or death.

Flowers had previously dated a woman who was dating Brandon Green, now 33. Flowers and his former girlfriend were at another woman‚Äôs apartment when Green banged on the door but wasn‚Äôt allowed in, prosecutors say. He allegedly got a gun from his car, forced his way into the apartment and shot Flowers in the chest. The woman who lived in the apartment then shot Green, who survived. He was charged with second-degree murder.

A neighbor called 911 on March 20 and Seattle police officers forced their way into Straalsund's apartment, where they found Casey Stanley Henderson, now 22, choking Straalsund, who had severe head and facial injuries. Officers performed CPR but she never regained consciousness and died two days later. Henderson is charged with first-degree murder domestic violence. Both were University of Washington students and had casually dated for about six months.

Seattle police were called to a domestic disturbance and found Lampkin in his parked car in an alley outside his girlfriend‚Äôs apartment. The girlfriend, who was six months pregnant at the time, had fled but was interviewed by police a few days later. Lampkin died from a stab wound to his chest. His girlfriend has not been charged.

Al-Samarrai's body was found in the stairwell of an apartment complex. Omar "Flacco" Acevedo, a member of a street gang, had some kind of ongoing disagreement with Al-Samarrai. While hanging out with mutual friends at a Renton apartment, they argued, then took their dispute outside, where Al-Samarrai was shot once in the head. Acevedo was later arrested in Yakima for allegedly robbing a man at gunpoint, stealing his car and leading deputies on a high-speed pursuit. He was charged in April with second-degree murder in connection with Al-Samarrai‚Äôs death.

Whitmore had apparently threatened to shoot Darion Lipsey, which enraged Lipsey, according to prosecutors. Lipsey, 22, and a woman drove around downtown Seattle until they spotted Whitmore and Purvis on Second Avenue Extension South. Lipsey jumped out of the car and confronted Whitmore, police say. While Whitmore was the intended target, Purvis apparently moved into the line of fire and both he and Whitmore were killed. Charged with two counts of first-degree murder, Lipsey was arrested in Federal Way in December.

Berry was found on a South Seattle sidewalk with multiple gunshot wounds and was pronounced dead at Harborview. He apparently moved here from Louisiana after Hurricane Katrina. He died less than 24 hours after posting bail on an unrelated firearms charge. No arrests have been made.
Ianniciello's wife and daughter returned home and found him dead in bed with a gunshot wound to the head. Ianniciello owned a produce distribution company in Kent. No arrests have been made.

McLaren was found shot to death in the parking lot at The Cove Apartment Homes. Police believe his death was retaliation for the fatal self-defense shooting of Dylan Lee Oman, 18, in Tacoma in January 2016. McLaren‚Äôs death is one of four which Federal Way police have attributed to a suspect who is in jail on unrelated charges but has not been charged in any of the killings.

Lyne had dated John Robert Charlton, now 38, for about a month and attended a Mariners game with him on April 8. The next day, Lyne‚Äôs ex-husband reported her missing and found she‚Äôd left her purse and cellphone in her house. Over the next nine days, Seattle police found her dismembered remains in three different locations. Charlton was arrested April 11 in Lake Stevens. Prosecutors say he strangled Lyne in her home, then dismembered her with a saw in her bathtub. He is charged with first-degree murder.

Several people called 911 to report hearing multiple gunshots and when police responded, DiTullio allegedly led officers on a five-mile pursuit before getting stuck in the driveway of a house on 21st Avenue Southwest. As officers yelled commands, one saw the door to the vehicle swing open and spotted DiTullio pointing an assault-style rifle at the officers. One officer fired multiple shots, killing DiTullio, who had a rifle on his lap.

Voegele was shot in the face in the breezeway of a Burien apartment building, allegedly by Gianni Cunningham, 17. According to charging papers, Cunningham claimed he was the intended target of a drive-by shooting but a resident at the apartment complex told police he‚Äôd seen, through his peephole, Cunningham playing with a 9-mm handgun. The resident also heard Voegele repeatedly tell Cunningham to put the gun away, then witnessed her getting shot. Cunningham has been charged with second-degree murder.

Phelps, who was visiting friends, was shot in the parking lot of a Burien apartment complex and died at Harborview. He was allegedly killed by a 14-year-old, who has been charged with second-degree murder, possession of a stolen firearm and burglary. Prosecutors are seeking to try the juvenile as an adult.

A no-bail warrant was issued in Jan. 2017 for the arrest of Juan Felipe Galeana-Madrigal, who was charged with first-degree murder in connection with Mendoza's death. According to prosecutors, Galeana-Madrigal shot Mendoza twice in the head because he believed Mendoza was an informant in a federal narcotics investigation. Mendoza, who apparently owed Galeana-Madrigal money, was an alleged drug distributor who sold heroin and meth.

Kelley, a Seattle resident, was smoking on the porch of a friend‚Äôs apartment in Federal Way when he was shot once in the back. His death is one of four that Federal Way police have attributed to a known suspect who is in custody on unrelated charges but has not been charged in connection with any of the fatal shootings.

Cohens, a Tacoma resident and the father of two young children, was found slumped over the wheel of his car. Federal Way police say there is evidence that drug activity was connected to his death. His death is one of four that Federal Way police have attributed to a known suspect who is in custody on unrelated charges but has not been charged in connection with any of the fatal shootings.

Gutierrez was out running with his dog when he was shot and found dead on a sidewalk. A University of Washington graduate and Navy veteran, he had been training for a marathon. His death is one of four that Federal Way police have attributed to a known suspect who is in custody on unrelated charges but has not been charged in connection with any of the fatal shootings.

Officers responded to a report of a fight and found Garnica lying in the street. He died at the scene. Police believe his killing is likely gang-related. No one has been arrested in connection with his death.
Webb was shot in the chest and was found lying outside a home. He died at Harborview. Seattle police interviewed his 94-year-old neighbor about the shooting but have made no arrests.

Tami A. Christianson was charged with second-degree murder, accused of killing her 15-month-old son in her parents' house near Redmond. Christianson, who has a history of mental illness and prescription-drug abuse, had apparently made comments about killing Brody and putting him up for adoption. According to charging documents, Brody's father and grandparents had tried to protect the child from his mother.

Mariah Phillips, 25, and Lee Dupay, 34, are each charged with second-degree murder domestic violence in connection with the death of their baby girl. Charging papers say the baby died from abuse and neglect, had numerous rib fractures and was severely malnourished. The couple's other children, twin 2-year-old girls, were placed with Child Protective Services.

Arbo was involved in a fight on May 2, when he was assaulted and knocked to the ground, smashing his head on a metal newspaper box. He died June 26 at Harborview. Antonio David Gomez, 32, has been charged with first-degree manslaughter.

Dacanay‚Äôs body was found by police in a stolen car in the parking lot of a SeaTac apartment complex on July 6. The medical examiner determined he died July 4 from multiple gunshot wounds. No arrests have been made.

Clayton was ambushed inside the trailer he shared with his father and was killed with guns stolen from his father‚Äôs locked gun safe. The trailer was then set ablaze. Dylan Scott Mullins, now 19, and Sebastian Gregg, now 18, were arrested in Montesano, Grays Harbor County, two days later when a trooper pulled them over in a stolen pickup. Police say both admitted to killing Clayton because Clayton had previously beat up Mullins. Mullins and Gregg are each charged with first-degree murder, first-degree arson and first-degree burglary.

Both Smith and Travis Pendley, now 31, were transients who were camping at Fenster Park on the Green River. Pendley allegedly accused Smith of stealing tools from his campsite and in a confrontation, fatally shot Smith, whose body was found in the woods by passersby the next day. Pendley was charged with second-degree murder, theft of a firearm and unlawful possession of a firearm.

Khamphouvong pulled his SUV into the driveway of a house in the 9300 block of 39th Avenue South and was immediately blocked in by another vehicle, whose occupants allegedly ordered him out of his SUV. Instead, Khamphouvong quickly reversed, slamming into the other vehicle as Kenny Am, now 21, opened fire, killing Khamphouvong. Seattle police say Am killed Khamphouvong in apparent retaliation for stealing a machine that makes fake credit cards. Am was charged with second-degree murder.

A passer-by called 911 after spotting Bolar's body just inside the doorway of her Madison Valley house. Bolar died from multiple gunshot wounds. There have been no arrests in connection with her death.

Martelli was apparently angry at his neighbor for borrowing tools and refusing to give them back. He allegedly fired a shotgun into his neighbor's car, injuring the man, who then attempted to drive to the police station but crashed before he got there. Police responded to Martelli's apartment, where Martelli fired at least once at officers. Two officers returned fire, killing the mentally ill man.

Campos, a transient woman living in a homeless encampment off 88th Avenue South, died of multiple gunshot wounds. Less than 24 hours later, a homeless man was fatally shot at the same encampment. There have been no arrests.
Dias, who lived in the same homeless encampment as Louisa Campos, was fatally shot less than 24 hours after she was gunned down and killed. There have been no arrests.

Police say Dominguez-Navarro was fatally shot and a 23-year-old man was gravely wounded in an apparent drug rip-off over $1,200 worth of marijuana. The men were shot as they sat in a car parked at a Tukwila apartment complex. Treston Baladez-Castillo, 20, was arrested in Hayden, Idaho, in September and is charged with first-degree murder, first-degree assault and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Barber was found dead at an apartment complex in Federal Way and police searched for two men in their 20s, possibly driving a white Chevrolet Malibu. Responding officers were surrounded by a group of 50 to 75 people, but no witnesses came forward. No arrests have been made.
Nein was shot to death and found in between buildings in a couple of apartment complexes in Kent. No one has been arrested in connection with Nein‚Äôs homicide.

Love was a construction worker from Oregon who was staying at the Motel 6 with two co-workers while working a local job. He got into an argument with suspect Rodney C. Wheeler, 39, who police say was baiting Love and a co-worker to fight and using racial slurs. Love was fatally shot in the chest in the motel parking lot. A second man, also a guest at the motel, was shot in the back by a stray bullet as he got out of the shower. Wheeler was arrested in October and charged with second-degree murder, second-degree assault and second-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Huynh and suspect Quang Ngoc Dinh were friends who attended a small gathering at Huynh's girlfriend's house in Kent. Dinh became angry because Huynh wanted to go to bed instead of staying up to continue drinking with Dinh. After allegedly threatening Huynh and his girlfriend with a kitchen knife, Dinh is accused of retrieving a handgun from his car, then firing through an open door, killing Huynh and grazing a 31-year-old Kent woman. Dinh was charged with first-degree murder and first-degree assault.

Hovey and some friends attended a house party in Burien. Hovey left and a short time later his friends found him on the ground outside with three gunshot wounds to the chest. The friends got him in a car and drove him to Highline Medical Center; Hovey was then transferred to Harborview, where he died. No arrests have been made.

Auburn police say a patrol officer responded to a vandalism call at an apartment complex and was with a citizen when Ell approached them, armed with a 3-foot long metal pipe. Police say Ell, who also had a knife sheathed on his belt, raised the pipe as if to swing it and ignored the officer's commands to drop it. The officer shot and killed Ell.

Apling and her estranged boyfriend, Rashied Mitchell, got into an argument inside Mitchell‚Äôs mother‚Äôs apartment when Apling went to pick up their children after she got off work. Mitchell, 46, is accused of shooting Apling in front of the children, then shooting himself in the head. Mitchell, who has a lengthy history of domestic-violence assaults, survived and was charged with first-degree murder.

Sandeep Kaur, a 34-year-old expectant mother, was very close to full term when she attempted suicide by setting herself on fire. She delivered her baby, who was dubbed Baby Boy Singh, but he lived less than three hours. His death was ruled a homicide. Kaur died a month later at Harborview.

Sloboda apparently cut off a driver while driving to visit his wife and newborn at the hospital. He was chased by the other driver, so went to his brother's apartment in Federal Way, where he stayed for about an hour. After leaving his brother's home, Sloboda was found fatally shot in his car. No one has been arrested in connection with his death.

Seattle police officers, who were in Pioneer Square at bar closing time, heard several gunshots and found Perry dead from a gunshot wound to the head in a parking lot at Occidental and Washington. No arrests have been made.

Gonclaves was stabbed by a stranger at the Tukwila-International Boulevard Link Light Rail station and died a short time later at Harborview. Based on witness descriptions, officers tracked down Mehmet Ali Whicker, 30, nearby. Police say he had blood on his hands and clothes. Whicker, who has an extensive criminal history in multiple states, was charged with second-degree murder.

Auburn police say Valdez-Herrera was inside a vehicle when Alexander Joachin, then 16, fired numerous gunshots, killing him. Police say Joachin is a known gang member who told detectives he shot Valdez-Herrera because the 17-year-old had disrespected other gang members. Joachin was charged as an adult with second-degree murder.

Federal Way police responded to a domestic dispute between two adult brothers and arrived at a mobile-home park to find a number of family members had locked themselves in a room in a mobile home, fearing for their safety. They were helped out a window by officers. Ricardo Hernandez, 21, was armed with a butcher knife and is alleged to have told officers, "I don't have the guts to kill myself; you're going to have to do it for me." He was fatally shot by two officers.

A Seattle police sergeant shot and killed Taylor after encountering a fight between Taylor and another man near the The Jungle homeless encampment as city crews and police were working to move people out of the camp. Taylor was armed with a knife and was apparently attacking the second man when he was shot. Police recovered a knife at the scene.

Kent police were serving a search warrant as part of a fraudulent-activity investigation and encountered Reddeck, who lived at the house and was armed with a handgun. Two detectives and a patrol officer fired at him; Reddeck later died at Harborview.

Davis, the mother of three young children who was five months pregnant with her fourth child, was despondent and apparently suicidal when her boyfriend contacted a deputy and asked him to conduct a welfare check on her. No one answered the door and two deputies entered the house, where they found Davis armed with a handgun. Both deputies fired, killing Davis. Deputies recovered two rifles and a loaded handgun from the bedroom where she was shot.

Police were called to a fight among family members at a home in Kent and found Leuma unresponsive in the street outside. He died at the scene. Leuma died from a blunt-force injury to the head and acute combined alcohol and methamphetamine intoxication. There have been no arrests.

Officers responded to reports of a shooting inside a vehicle and found Barber in the backseat. He died at the scene. Three other people were in the car and police identified Larry Edward Thomas Jr., a 23-year-old passenger, as the shooter. Police say he couldn't provide a reason, other than that he had taken PCP before the shooting. Thomas was charged with second-degree murder and second-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Frost and two alleged accomplices, Jacob Mezich and Andrew Carpenter, kicked down the door of a Shoreline condominium to steal drugs, believing the home was empty because the owner was in jail. Frost, who was armed with an AR-15 rifle, was shot and killed by the condo owner‚Äôs roommate. Mezich, 26, and Carpenter, 27, fled but were arrested a few days later and charged with first-degree burglary and attempted first-degree robbery. The man who killed Frost has not been charged with a crime.

Witnesses told police that a gunman ran up to Osborn-Bash on the street early on Nov. 13th, shot him multiple times, then fled in a white SUV. The witnesses were unable to provide a detailed suspect description. Osborn-Bash died the next day at Harborview. No one has been arrested.

On Nov. 2, Bacani and a 27-year-old man were outside a Shoreline home talking to Reuben Melegrito, a "social friend" who showed up unannounced. Melegrito, an admitted gang member, suddenly opened fire after a minor argument, police say. Bacani, who was shot twice, died Nov. 20 at Harborview. The 27-year-old was shot four times, but survived. Melegrito, 27, was arrested at his family‚Äôs home in Renton and charged with second-degree murder and attempted second-degree murder.

Sheikh was on a Metro bus in Renton on Nov. 29 and chatted with Faisal Adan, 22, an old acquaintance. Adan is accused of pulling out a revolver and shooting Sheikh for no apparent reason in front of numerous passengers, then threatening the bus driver with the gun as he demanded to be let off the bus. Adan was arrested a short time later and is charged with second-degree murder, second-degree assault and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm. Sheikh died Dec. 1st at Harborview.

Nguyen, walking home after work, was attacked in an attempted purse snatching. She struggled with her assailant and was shot multiple times. He fled without her purse. Nguyen died a short time later at Harborview. No one has been arrested in connection with her killing.

Perez-Placencia was fatally shot by her ex-boyfriend, 24-year-old Erick Ortuno-Perez. He also shot another woman in the leg before fatally shooting himself. Perez-Placencia and Ortuno-Perez were parents of a 4-year-old daughter. Perez-Placencia had obtained a protection order against Ortuno-Perez, who police say was controlling, abusive and had previously threatened to kill her and himself.

Hicks was attending a gathering at a Federal Way apartment complex and was shot during an argument, apparently over possible stolen property. He later died at Harborview. There have been no arrests in connection with his death.

Redmond fire crews responded to a fire alarm at an apartment building, where about 100 people were attending a party in a recreation room. There was no fire, but firefighters heard what sounded like a gunshot and called for police, who found Anguiano dead from a gunshot wound to the neck. No arrests have been made.

Ortiz was fatally shot during an ongoing argument over defaced gang graffiti. A then-17-year-old, Joshua Rios-Andrade, was charged as an adult with second-degree murder. According to Burien police, Ortiz was a gang member and Rios is an associate or member of a street gang in the greater Burien area.

On the night he was killed, Aber-Williams had been talking to a 23-year-old woman on Snapchat and she asked him to come to her apartment. Her boyfriend, Kevion Alexander, 25, was charged with first-degree murder, accused of ambushing and shooting Aber-Williams in the back of the head to rob him of cash, jewelry and drugs.

Thomas died from a stab wound to the back that penetrated his heart and aorta. His right eye was also severely burned, likely from a portable propane torch found at the scene. Luke Carlson, 24, was arrested early the next morning outside a restaurant in SeaTac after Carlson's father called 911 to report Thomas' death and told police his son admitted to the killing. Carlson has been charged with second-degree murder.

Trinh was asleep in bed when he was struck in the head by a bullet that came in through his bedroom wall. Deputies found numerous shell casings on the ground outside a neighbor's house and bullet holes in its fa√ßade. Bullet holes were also found in a car parked outside the home. No one has been arrested in connection with his death.

Ka'Deidre Rials, now 24, and two teen girls had allegedly broken into several cars and stolen purses and credit cards at Beaver Lake Park in Sammamish. Radcliffe, after seeing his car had been prowled, grabbed a gun from his trunk and began firing at the windshield of Rials' SUV. He was run over and dragged by the vehicle. The King County Medical Examiner ruled Radcliffe's death a homicide. Rials pleaded guilty to felony hit-and-run causing death, plus second-degree identity theft and two counts of second-degree car prowl on Jan. 17. Rials was sentenced Feb. 9 to just under 4 ¬Ω years in prison, with credit for the 377 days she spent in jail.

King County sheriff's deputies investigating the Jan. 25 death of Moises Radcliffe were outside a Des Moines apartment and preparing a ruse to get a 16-year-old boy to come out and talk to them. The sheriff's office says the boy and Dunlap-Gittens were armed with handguns when they approached the deputies' unmarked police van. The deputies jumped out of the van, ordered the teens to drop their weapons, and say one of them - presumably Dunlap-Gittens - fired at them. Two detectives returned fire, mortally wounding Dunlap-Gittens. The 16-year-old fled but was arrested the next day and was charged with first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Pitts, who was looking to buy drugs, was gunned down outside a building about 20 minutes after an argument with the occupants of a dark green van. As Pitt was negotiating a drug deal with another person, Seattle police say, Darryl Peterson, wearing a mask, walked up to Pitts, shot him and fled. Peterson, now 37, was pulled over in a traffic stop on Feb. 6 in the dark green van. A Level 3 sex offender who served prison time for rape, he was charged with first-degree murder and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Ana Fevaleaki, now 34, has been charged with second-degree murder, accused of causing fatal head and abdominal injuries to her boyfriend's 2-year-old son. Fevaleaki claimed Angelo had fallen off a chair and bumped his head the day before she took him to Harborview Medical Center on Feb. 4, but doctors determined his fatal injury happened within hours of his receiving medical treatment.

Plunkett had been drinking at JJ's Bar and Grill when he went outside to smoke. He was found dead from a gunshot to the chest in the driver's seat of his black Mercedes-Benz. A spent .45-caliber shell casing was found near his feet, along with marijuana. According to police, detectives are actively working the case and are awaiting lab results on evidence sent to the State Patrol Crime Lab for analysis.

Liam Carter, then 17, was housesitting and invited Spann, his childhood friend, over to stay with him. The homeowner had given Carter a .38-caliber revolver to protect the house, which had previously been burglarized. Carter and Spann were hanging out, smoking marijuana and playing with the gun when they decided to play Russian roulette and Spann was shot. Detectives say Carter, who called 911, stopped CPR on his dying friend to stage the scene to make it look like the gun fell and accidentally discharged. Carter was charged as an adult with first-degree manslaughter.

Someone called 911 and requested police perform a welfare check on Draman, a homeless man who was moaning as he lay curled up by a fence outside a cross-fit center. Draman died at the scene from multiple stab wounds. No arrests have been made.

Police say Stokes, armed with a machete, went in and out of a house occupied by another man. About six officers from Des Moines, Tukwila and Kent attempted to get Stokes to drop the weapon, but police say he did not comply with their orders. He was fatally shot by a Kent police officer. The other officers on the scene did not fire.

Ramirez and Dario Martinez Castro, 18, were at a house party when they got into a fight over which man makes more money. Other partygoers broke up the fight and the two young men shook hands. Martinez, who lived nearby, left the party and returned a short time later with a handgun. Police say he stood in the front doorway and fired six times at Ramirez. Martinez, who fled before turning himself in to police, was charged with first-degree murder.

A relative discovered the body of David Swanson, 62, in the garage of his Kirkland home on April 16 and called police. Officers found his wife, Estelle Swanson, 66, dead in the kitchen. The King County Medical Examiner estimated the couple had died a week earlier, on April 9. Estelle Swanson died from multiple sharp-force injuries and David Swanson from a self-inflicted injury to his neck. The case was investigated as a murder-suicide.
Lubben, who also used the alias Makaiel Blackwell, was found with a gunshot wound to the head in a stairwell of the Sunset View Apartments hours after he had been killed. No arrests have been made.

Police say three people stalked Alvarez for blocks and then fatally shot him as he stepped off a Metro bus in a daytime killing that was part of an ongoing Hispanic gang war in South Seattle and South King County. Miguel Bejar, 22, and Antonio Inda, now 16, have both been charged with second-degree murder. A King County Superior Court judge ruled Jan. 31 that Inda, who was 15 at the time of the shooting, will be prosecuted as an adult. Police also arrested Alondra "Mama Pepa" Garcia Garcia, 20, who allegedly drove Bejar and Inda to and from the shooting scene. She has been charged with first-degree rendering criminal assistance.

Seattle police officers heard multiple gunshots, saw several people run from the area and discovered Williams dead in the parking lot of a business. One man was detained and questioned, then released. Officers found a handgun at the scene. No arrests have been made.

Plata appeared to be waiting for someone at a gas station when two men approached and shot him numerous times. They then fled in a vehicle. According to police sources, Plata was killed in retaliation for the shooting death of Arturo Marcial Alvarez less than nine hours earlier in Federal Way as part of an ongoing war between rival Hispanic street gangs. No one has been arrested.

Matamoros and a 16-year-old boy were shot behind a gas station. The 16-year-old was able to make it inside the station's convenience store and ask the clerk to call 911. Matamoros died outside from a gunshot wound to the neck. There have been no arrests.

Police were called after Butts and his then-17-year-old sister stole beer and snacks from a 7-Eleven store. As officers tried to take Butts into custody, his sister is accused of throwing a soda bottle at an officer's head and attempting to choke him, enabling Butts to get free. Several officers chased Butts, who shot Officer Elizabeth Kennedy, but her ballistic vest stopped the bullet. She returned fire, Butts fell, but then he shot Officer Hudson Kang in the face. Kennedy and five other officers opened fire and killed Butts. Kang was hospitalized for several days but survived.

Jimerson, who died from a gunshot to the head, and a male companion, who suffered multiple gunshot wounds, were found inside a car near Fire Station 13. Jimerson and the injured man were shot outside a bar in Kent, then drove themselves to the area where they were found. Jimerson's death is believed to be gang-related. No arrests have been made.

Outen and William Harrell, now 35, had dated for more than four years and lived a transient lifestyle. When a man knocked on the door of the couple's RV to borrow some gas cans, Outen hid a heroin pipe so he wouldn't see it. Harrell then became enraged and accused Outen of stealing his money and drugs, and stabbed her in the chest with a kitchen knife, police say. Harrell is charged with second-degree murder domestic violence.

Shabazz was inside a vehicle in the parking lot of Borrachini's Bakery in Seattle when she was shot numerous times in what was believed to be a gang-related shooting. A man inside the bakery also suffered a non-life-threatening gunshot wound. No arrests have been made.

Two women got into a fight in the bathroom at the Taradise Caf√© and the fight spilled out into the street. Little went to talk to one of the women when another man wearing a hoodie walked up to him and shot him in the head. Detectives identified Billy Dawayne Williams, 30, of Albany, Ore., as the gunman; he was charged with first-degree murder and unlawful possession of a firearm. Williams remains at large.
Thomas was attending a gathering at Alki Beach when he was shot numerous times. The suspected shooter fled in a vehicle. No arrests have been made.

A passerby discovered Ayson's body in a ravine on July 11. A month earlier, his purchase of $8 worth of marijuana had attracted the attention of a King County sheriff's deputy, who witnessed Ayson, a homeless man, buy pot from Malcolm McGee, now 26. The next day, police say, McGee drove Ayson to a dead-end street and shot him multiple times. McGee was arrested Aug. 1 and is charged with second-degree murder.

Graham's body was found in a homeless encampment and his death was initially reported as a drug overdose before detectives determined he had been assaulted. According to court records, Graham demanded drugs and money from a homeless woman, then struck her. Two men - Aaron "AJ" Rillera, 44, and Hung Minh "Pete" Pham, 47 - allegedly struck Graham in the head with baseball bats. Rillera was arrested that day and Pham, who has a violent criminal history, was arrested July 10. Both men have been charged with second-degree murder.

Jackson died from a gunshot wound to her neck after getting into a fight with her former roommate in the parking lot of the Avenue Apartments. Others at the scene held the now-29-year-old woman down until police arrived. Though a judge found probable cause to hold her on investigation of homicide, she was released from jail two days later. According to the King County Sheriff's Office, no criminal charges have been filed and detectives believe the shooting was accidental.

Thordarson's brother returned to the home the siblings shared and found her bloody and unresponsive, lying face down on the living-room floor with a knife nearby. A neighbor later told officers Thordarson's nephew, Javen Thordarson, 18, had been seen leaving the house with something in his hand. Javen Thordarson was arrested that night and charged with second-degree murder.

A woman called 911 after Obet, who was armed with a knife, walked into her house, demanded money, and then left when she told him to leave. Auburn police say he went to a second house but then ran away and attempted to carjack a female driver. Officer Jeff Nelson fired at Obet, who died at the scene from multiple gunshot wounds.

Several people called 911 to report a man with a knife, shouting "I am the Creator" and "I am the killer"; he attempted to stab a man, who fired a gun into the ground to stop Le from advancing, according to the King County Sheriff's Office. The sheriff's office said three deputies confronted Le, who refused commands to drop "what they thought was a knife." Two deputies fired Tasers, with one of them hitting Le, but it had no effect. When Le moved toward deputies, Deputy Cesar Molina shot him three times. A pen was found nearby.

Lyles, a pregnant mother of four, called 911 to report a burglary. Seattle police Officers Jason Anderson and Steven McNew responded, but didn't find any evidence of a break-in. Police say Lyles suddenly brandished a knife and attempted to cut one of the officers. Both fired at her, killing her. The police department later determined Anderson and McNew used reasonable force.

Pimentel was eating outside a Dick's Drive-In with two friends as a large crowd, many of them talking loudly, was gathered outside the restaurant. Leon Caril II, who was across the street, apparently became annoyed at the crowd and started pitching items at people. Police say he threw a two-liter soda bottle, which rolled toward one of Pimentel's friends, who told Caril, "That's a good way to get your ass kicked." Caril, 38, charged across the street armed with a Bowie knife and stabbed Pimentel three times, according to prosecutors. He was arrested minutes later in a nearby alley. Caril was charged with second-degree murder.

According to Kent police, Joseph-McDade failed to pull over for a traffic stop, then led police on a one-mile pursuit at speeds reaching 60 mph. An officer briefly stopped the vehicle using a Pursuit Intervention Technique (PIT) maneuver, but Joseph-McDade continued driving toward Officer William Davis, who had gotten out of his patrol car to approach the vehicle. Davis fired twice, striking Joseph-McDade both times.

After attending a wedding in South Lake Union, Cameron Espitia, 31, wanted to go to an after-party but his wife, Jennifer, wanted to go home. The two got into an Uber and were arguing when police say Cameron Espitia pulled out a handgun, shot his wife in the back of the head and had the driver drop him off. Cameron Espitia was arrested a short time later and claimed he'd fallen asleep in some bushes and didn't recall anything after getting into the Uber. He is charged with second-degree murder domestic violence.

Muipu and her boyfriend, Chris Tavita, were playing with a Taser and a .45-caliber handgun when Tavita, 23, pointed what he apparently thought was an unloaded weapon at Muipu's face and pulled the trigger. She died at the scene. Police say Tavita initially got his younger siblings to lie for him, telling detectives Muipu shot herself in the face while spinning the gun around on her finger. His 12-year-old brother later called a detective and explained what happened. Tavita is charged with first-degree manslaughter domestic violence.

Curry was killed and another man wounded in a shooting next to Rainier Play Field. Lloyd Hinton, 43, was the alleged driver of a green Ford Expedition used in the shooting committed by an as-yet unidentified gunman. Hinton was charged with second-degree murder and first-degree assault. The gunman has not been arrested.

Stewart was a friend of Shamar Curry, 32, who was fatally shot near the Rainier Play Field on July 9. Stewart was part of a group gathered at a memorial for Curry at the shooting scene when someone in a passing car opened fire, killing Stewart. No arrests have been made.

A witness told King County sheriff's detectives that Mitchell and Jose Jaimes Luna, also 21, were on a porch talking when Jaimes suddenly pulled out a gun, shot Mitchell and then himself. Both men died from gunshot wounds to the head. The King County Medical Examiner ruled Mitchell's death a homicide and determined Jaimes committed suicide.

Passengers in two vehicles were exchanging gunfire as they drove through the area at high speed on July 1. Thomas, 20, was a passenger in one of the cars and was shot in the head. She died from her injuries at Harborview Medical Center on Aug. 7. No arrests have been made.

Nelson's ex-girlfriend called 911 after Nelson showed up at her workplace, a hookah lounge in a Kent strip mall, in violation of a domestic-violence no-contact order. When Kent police arrived, Nelson ran to his vehicle, started the engine and allegedly dragged an officer and police dog in his attempt to get away. Two officers fired at Nelson, killing him at the scene.

Police say Keat and Tramaine Claiborne, now 28, arrived in a car together at a gas station and got into a fight. Claiborne is accused of pulling out a gun and firing twice into Keat's back as Keat tried to run away. Claiborne then stood over Keat and fired at least three more times into his prone body. Claiborne was arrested in a nearby alley and charged with second-degree murder.

King County sheriff's deputies responded to Skyway Park Bowl after several people called 911 to report that two men had been shot in the bowling alley's bar area. Robinson was pronounced dead at the scene and Gantz died a short time later at Harborview Medical Center. No arrests have been made.

Elder Carceres, now 30, and Luci Lucarelli, 32, are accused of tying Finney up in his motel room, beating him, putting a plastic bag over his head and repeatedly stabbing him, then stealing a large stash of methamphetamines. At the time of his arrest, Carceres was being investigated for arson; earlier in the summer, he had allegedly set fire to a tent Finney was in. Carceres and Lucarelli are both charged with second-degree murder.

Moss, who lived in a tent in a homeless encampment beneath the West Seattle Bridge, accused Daniel Markishtum, 34, of stealing something from his tent. During their argument, Markishtum - who also appeared to be homeless - fired a shot, striking Moss and grazing the face of a second man who had tried to mediate. Markishtum was arrested a week and a half later in Pioneer Square. Originally charged with second-degree murder, Markishtum pleaded guilty in November to second-degree manslaughter and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm and was sentenced to nearly four years in prison.

Police say Aregay Tesfamariam, 50, attacked his wife, Ferede-Tesema, with a steak knife in the kitchen of their Kent home and their adult son tried to intervene. Ferede-Tesema ran outside, her husband chased her and resumed his attack. Her death was witnessed by her son and a passing mailman. Tesfamariam, who apparently had a long history of domestic violence against his wife, is charged with premeditated first-degree murder.

Lopez, who went by the nickname "Peachy", went to Westcrest Park to sell some marijuana to a couple other teens and was robbed and stabbed to death. Two weeks later, Seattle police arrested Jonatan Islas Martinez, 18; Elizabeth Cabrera Aparicio, 17; and Diego Carballo Oliveros, 16. All three have been charged in adult court with first-degree murder.

A 35-year-old homeowner told King County sheriff's deputies he heard a noise in the bedroom where his two toddlers were sleeping and went to investigate. Seeing two people attempting to break into his house through a window, the homeowner fired numerous shots, killing Grant, as the second would-be intruder ran away. No criminal charges were filed against the homeowner.

Morris and Jamal Austin, 21, got into an argument at a South Seattle convenience store, which turned into a fight out on the street. Morris appeared to be winning the fistfight when Austin then pulled out a gun and started shooting, hitting Morris. Austin ran from the scene and Morris collapsed inside a nearby bar. Austin later turned himself in to police in Kent and was charged with second-degree murder.

Police say Velasquez's ex-girlfriend, Anna Kasparova, used a ruse to lure Velasquez out of his house, then walked across the street and took cover as Velasquez got into her car to park it. The alleged gunman, Abel Linares Montejo, pulled Velasquez out of the vehicle, shot him several times and ran off. Kasparova, 21, was arrested at her mother's house in Burien the next day. Montejo, 19, was arrested at an Auburn trailer park on Oct. 4. Both are charged with premeditated first-degree murder.

According to police, Jose Luis Ramirez Inda, 43, was drinking with four other men in the parking lot of an apartment complex when they were joined by Medina. Medina, who was also drunk, made some comments that angered Inda and the two began fighting. Medina tried to leave but Inda kept going after him. The other men tried to stop Inda, who punched Medina, causing him to fall and hit his head on the concrete driveway. Inda is charged with first-degree manslaughter.

Lee, accompanied by a 28-year-old man, got into a confrontation with Nguyen and a 46-year-old man outside a Kent karaoke bar. According to Kent police, Lee pulled a gun and held it to his side as he continued yelling, which is when the 46-year-old shot Lee in the head. As Lee fell to the ground and dropped his gun, the 28-year-old picked up the weapon as the 46-year-old fired at him. The 28-year-old returned fire, fatally shooting Nguyen and injuring the 46-year-old, who survived. No charges have been filed and the case remains under investigation.

During a fight inside a Sodo restaurant, Mai was stabbed in the chest; he died at the scene. A couple days later, the U.S. Marshals Service arrested a 24-year-old Edmonds man on investigation of homicide but he was released from jail pending further investigation. The case is still under review by King County prosecutors.

Shinelle Stills, who had been married to Samuel Stills for 17 years, had moved out of the family's SeaTac home in May and was in the process of getting a divorce. She returned to the house to visit her son and pets when the couple argued and Samuel Stills accused her of having relationships with other men. He is accused of grabbing a handgun, shooting her once in the back, then standing over her and shooting her three or four more times. Samuel Stills then went into his bedroom and shot himself once under the chin. He survived and is charged with first-degree murder domestic violence.

Prosecutors say friends Austin Glore, 17, and Michael Sample, 20, arranged to meet Pearson outside a Denny's restaurant in Auburn for a drug deal. Glore gave Pearson a backpack containing electronics, jewelry and money in exchange for 300 Xanax pills and 20 Percocet pills. Glore apparently believed he had been ripped off and chased after Pearson. The two fought and Pearson pulled a knife but dropped it after getting punched. Glore is accused of picking up the knife and repeatedly stabbing Pearson. Glore, who was arrested the next day in North Bend, is charged in adult court with second-degree murder. Sample, who allegedly drove Glore from the scene, is charged with second-degree rendering criminal assistance.

Sweezer's partially burned body was found on the side of the road near Lake Tapps; her vehicle was later found abandoned with a large amount of blood in the trunk. Detectives believe she was killed inside her house in Kent after she apparently surprised Lance Rougeau, now 26, as he burglarized the residence. There, detectives found a dehydrated 4-month-old baby who had been left in her crib. The homicide is being investigated by Pierce County sheriff's detectives because Sweezer's body was discovered in Pierce County. Rougeau was arrested the next day. He is charged in Pierce County Superior Court with first-degree murder and first-degree burglary.

Hawkins, who suffered a gunshot wound to the head, was driven to St. Francis Hospital and dumped from a vehicle, which was later found abandoned outside Federal Way city limits. Police say it's possible she was shot and killed outside the city before being driven to the hospital. No arrests have been made; the investigation is ongoing.

Officers responded to reports of shots fired in an alley and found two wounded men in a parking lot, where witnesses said there had been a disturbance between a group of people just before the shooting. Fesseha died at Harborview Medical Center from a gunshot wound to the head; a second man in his 20s survived his injuries. No arrests have been made.

Police say Lightfeather was threatening two other men with a gun when someone called 911. Federal Way police responded and two officers fired simultaneously at Lightfeather when he pointed his gun at the officers.

Brister and Myles died from multiple gunshot wounds and a second man was injured in an early-morning shooting in Belltown. Seattle police say Jeremy Simmons, 35, apparently targeted Brister because her boyfriend had previously stolen drugs and money from him. The surviving victim told police two men were involved in the shooting. Simmons was arrested Dec. 11 at the California-Mexico border and is charged with two counts of first-degree murder and one count of first-degree assault. His suspected accomplice has not been arrested.

Stonney Rivers, 50, is accused of shooting Cabrera in the face during a drug robbery at a Kent motel. Theneious Swafford, 47, is accused of driving Rivers to and from the motel. Days later, both suspects were booked into jail on unrelated warrants. Rivers, who was released from prison in 2015 after then-Gov. Christine Gregoire commuted his life sentence, and Swafford are both charged with first-degree murder.

A couple days after a 27-year-old man punched his female roommate, Peltier, the woman's ex-boyfriend, came to their house, armed himself with a rifle and confronted the 27-year-old in a bedroom, according to sheriff's detectives. Peltier fired the rifle at the roommate at least once and the 27-year-old fired back, shooting Peltier twice in the chest with a 9-mm handgun. The 27-year-old was arrested hours later in Thurston County; King County prosecutors determined he fatally shot Peltier in self-defense. He pleaded guilty to second-degree unlawful possession of a firearm and fourth-degree assault and was sentenced to one month in jail.

Crouse, of Maple Valley, and a 17-year-old boy from Newcastle both attended a party in an unoccupied unit at the Alcove Apartments. They stepped out into the hall and a witness reported hearing an argument, followed by gunshots. They apparently opened fire on each other: Crouse died from multiple gunshot wounds and the 17-year-old survived. The case remains under investigation.

Witnesses told sheriff's deputies that Su was talking with a group of men when an argument erupted and one of the men shot Su, who died at the scene from multiple gunshot wounds. No arrests have been made.

On Nov. 10, a resident of an apartment complex called 911 to request a welfare check after seeing a man covered in blood wandering around the parking lot. Police arrived and summoned medics, who took Day to Harborview Medical Center, where he died from a gunshot wound to the head five days later. Malik Tupac Lee, 20, was charged in December with second-degree murder and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Police went to check on Ricardo "Rick" Nicolini, a 58-year-old Seattle dentist, on Nov. 18 after he failed to show up for an appointment. Officers found his body, along with that of his wife, Mary Ellen Nicolini, 65, and their son, 23-year-old Richard Nicolini. Investigators determined that Richard Nicolini shot both of his parents in the head, then turned the gun on himself. The King County Medical Examiner ruled all three died the day before their bodies were found.

Seattle police responded to a shots-fired call and another 911 call reporting that a man was down. Medics attempted CPR on Shears, but he died at the scene from multiple gunshot wounds. No arrests have been made.

For a week before her death, Zaragoza had told friends she suspected she was being followed by her ex-boyfriend, Erik Guzman Naranjo. On the night she was killed, she and a male friend drove to a smoke shop, where Zaragoza was shot in the head after Naranjo allegedly busted the driver's side window of her car with the butt of a gun. Her friend fled and was not hurt. Naranjo, 22, was arrested two days later in Lake Oswego, Ore. and charged with first-degree murder domestic violence.

Prosecutors say Hector Galeano ‚Äî who had been released weeks earlier from a juvenile rehabilitation facility for a 2016 shooting in Auburn - arranged through friends to buy $500 worth of marijuana from Mattson. Galeano, 18, got into Mattson's car and as Mattson measured out the pot, he showed Galeano and another friend thousands of dollars he kept in a fabric bag. According to police, Galeano scooped up the cash and pointed a gun at Mattson, then ran back to the car he had arrived in. Mattson chased Galeano, who shot him multiple times. Galeano turned himself in to Kent police hours later and is charged with first-degree murder and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Police say Jonathan Scott accompanied a woman to the Newport Apartments to get her 10-month-old child back from the baby's father, who lived there. The woman and Eliysares, who was the child's father's roommate, got into an argument in the parking lot; Scott inserted himself into their dispute, then shot Eliysares in the chest. Scott was arrested two days later in Kent and claimed he shot Eliysares in self-defense, but police say Eliysares was unarmed. Scott is charged with second-degree murder and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Police responded to a shots-fired call and found Bardwell unconscious and unresponsive. Detectives believe Bardwell, who died from multiple gunshot wounds, was targeted as a result of his involvement in criminal and drug-related activity. The case is actively being investigated.

D'Andre Glaspy, 24, is accused of torturing and beating his girlfriend's toddler son, Moses. Glaspy called 911 to report the child was unresponsive and Moses died at the scene. An autopsy showed that Moses suffered several broken ribs, a fractured pelvis, a heart rupture and damage to his liver, pancreas and bowels; he also suffered at least six blows to the head and had a number of old injuries, including broken bones and partially-healed ribs. Glaspy is charged with second-degree murder.

Police say Marhowe Kifle, 24, stalked and ambushed Nejash after spotting him entering a marijuana dispensary. Kifle is accused of following Nejash, who was a passenger in a red Ford Taurus, and firing at least six rounds into the passenger side of the Taurus. The driver of the Taurus drove Nejash to Harborview Medical Center, where he died. Kifle, who was out on bail for a July drive-by shooting, was arrested Jan. 2 in Lynnwood. He is charged with first-degree murder.

Seattle police responded to a report of an armed robbery at Northgate Mall, then learned two suspects got into a confrontation with the manager of a North Seattle apartment complex a short time later. A female suspect was taken into custody on Holman Road Northwest but Gray, the male suspect, drove off, leading police on a pursuit that ended in Magnuson Park. Police say Gray fired out his window at officers, then at the park's boat ramp. He got out of his car and was confronted by seven officers, who all fired at Gray when he apparently reached for something in his waistband. Police say a gun was found near his body.
Farah, of Federal Way, was a passenger in a vehicle when someone opened fire on the car. He was driven to Harborview Medical Center, where he was pronounced dead. No arrests have been made.

The bodies of Asminin and his girlfriend, Marina Shamshurina, also 27, were discovered when their apartment manager went to check on the couple because he hadn't seen them in a few days. Asminin died from a gunshot wound to the torso and Shamshurina died from a self-inflicted gunshot wound to the head. The case was investigated as a murder-suicide.

Kirkland police responded to the Emerson Apartments after neighbors reported hearing screams and possible gunshots. Tade, who was reportedly carrying an assault rifle, was shot by at least one officer and died at the scene from multiple gunshot wounds.

Sharon Griffin, a resident of an assisted-living facility in the Central District, was shot in the head by her 70-year-old husband, Gary Griffin, and died at the scene. Gary Griffin later died at Harborview Medical Center from a self-inflicted gunshot wound. Their deaths were investigated as a murder-suicide.

Ochs, who lived in Port Orchard, was the victim of a brutal assault outside the Hawthorne Suites Hotel on Dec. 15. He suffered severe head trauma and died six days later at Harborview Medical Center from blunt-force injuries to his head and torso. Detectives do not believe this was a random attack and think the suspect is someone known to Ochs. The case remains an active investigation. No arrests have been made.

A 21-year-old woman, a friend of Dearden's, was playing around with her uncle's gun and pointed it at Dearden's head. She pulled the trigger, apparently thinking the 9-mm handgun was unloaded. Police believe the shooting may have been accidental but are still investigating. The woman is not in custody.

Sherrard was shot once in the chest in a hotel parking lot and died at Harborview Medical Center. Jacob Thiel, now 23, was found hiding nearby. He was charged with second-degree murder for allegedly shooting Sherrard because he believed Sherrard had stolen Thiel’s cellphone and other electronics.

Co-workers Garcia and Tapia were having drinks at the Taradise Café, a bar patronized by Merle “Chucky” Buchanan. When Tapia was kicked out for being intoxicated, he struck up a conversation with Buchanan outside while Garcia waited nearby. After about 15 minutes, surveillance footage showed Buchanan shooting Tapia in the face and Garcia in the head before driving away. Buchanan, now 27, turned himself in to police two months later and was charged with two counts of second-degree murder.

A woman who lives near the building where Benegas lived called 911 after finding human remains in a suitcase. The medical examiner determined Benegas died from multiple stab wounds and decapitation. Tukwila police arrested Benegas’ cousin, Rosalio Ramos Ramos, now 38. Ramos, who has been charged with second-degree murder, was in the country illegally and had been previously deported to Honduras four times.

Ayers was tortured, raped and stabbed by a man who, choosing at random, walked into her Lake City house through her unlocked back door. Her killer set her body on fire in an effort to destroy DNA evidence. Seattle police arrested Michael Giordano, now 24, in Pioneer Square. He was charged with aggravated first-degree murder.

Hernandez’s 9-year-old daughter called 911 on Dec. 14, 2017, and reported that her brother, Heriberto Alcantar Hernandez, was strangling and punching their mother. Hernandez, found on the ground outside the house, was airlifted to Harborview Medical Center, where doctors found the blade of a 5-inch knife in her skull. Alcantar, now 21, was arrested at a bus stop a mile from the family home with blood on his hands and clothing. He was initially charged with first-degree assault domestic violence but the charge was amended to second-degree murder domestic violence after his mother was taken off life support. Court records indicate Alcantar has been diagnosed with a serious mental illness and it appears unlikely he will be found competent to stand trial.

Pigford was stabbed multiple times in a Rainier Beach parking lot and died a short time later at Harborview Medical Center. Police interviewed a 34-year-old woman, who returned to the scene and said she had been injured in an altercation with Pigford. King County prosecutors declined to file criminal charges after determining the woman killed Pigford in self-defense.

In an attempted marijuana rip-off, Phung, who was in his car, was shot in the back in the parking lot at Renton High School and crashed his vehicle outside a church. Though police have not arrested the suspected shooter, two alleged accomplices were arrested. Dyonte Jackson, 20, was charged with first-degree murder. A then-17-year-old was initially charged as an adult with first-degree murder, but court records show he pleaded guilty to first-degree robbery in juvenile court and the murder charge was dismissed. In September, he was sentenced to 52 weeks

Tyson was shot after a fight broke out near a Chevron gas station where an open-air drug market is known to operate. A 17-year-old boy was wounded by gunfire and another 17-year-old was struck by a car as he ran away. There have been no arrests in connection with Tyson’s death, which may have been gang related.

Lewis was shot in the chest inside Studio Seven, a heavy-metal nightclub and hard-rock venue in Seattle’s Sodo neighborhood. Police have not identified the person who killed him. As a result of the shooting and several earlier incidents, the Washington State Liquor and Cannabis Board revoked the club’s liquor license and Studio Seven was permanently closed.
A woman heard gunshots and found Matthews, a Kent father of six, dead in her driveway. Though the woman knew Matthews, she wasn’t expecting him at her house. No arrests have been made.

Esparza and his mother were seated at a picnic table near a taco truck in South Park when they were swarmed by a group of people on Feb. 7. Esparza tried to run away and was shot four times. He later died at Harborview Medical Center. In July, Juan Macias, now 27, was arrested and charged with first-degree murder and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm in what was investigated as a gang-related shooting. Macias apparently believed that Esparza had stolen from him on New Year’s Day but court records don’t indicate what was allegedly taken.

Rodriguez was found dead, inside a vehicle, from a gunshot wound to the head. His death was initially investigated as a suicide before the King County Medical Examiner’s Office ruled it a homicide. There have been no arrests.

Responding to a report of a car prowler in Ravenna, Seattle police ended up pursuing a suspect, who exchanged gunfire with them. Police then received a report that someone had broken into a house eight blocks from the original scene and had stolen a car at gunpoint. The suspect, later identified as Seavers, crashed the car and was shot several times inside the vehicle as officers tried to take him into custody. A police video showed Seavers ignoring officers’ commands and searching the back seat and rear floorboard with his hand. Police later found a gun inside the vehicle.

On March 8, someone summoned medical aid for the baby boy, who was taken to Seattle Children’s hospital. The following day, doctors contacted police and reported that Loki was the victim of child abuse. At the time of his death from brain injury, he had multiple rib fractures in various stages of healing. No one was arrested because police were unable to determine who was responsible for his fatal injuries.

A friend went to Byrnes’ Wallingford home and found her dead. Byrnes’ throat had been slashed and she had been stabbed 60 to 70 times. In late April, prosecutors charged Byrnes’ roommate, Ian Flaherty, with first-degree murder. Byrnes’ family told police she had been attempting to evict Flaherty, now 26, because he wasn’t paying his share of expenses.

Price was beaten on Feb. 10, 2017 and the attack left him paralyzed and in a mostly-comatose state. A relative transferred Price to a rehabilitation center in Arizona, where he died from his injuries. Police are investigating his death as a homicide but have made no arrests.

Duncan, who was homeless, was shot in the face on a Burien street and died two days later. The shooting was witnessed by a female motorist and was captured by video-surveillance cameras at a nearby business. On March 20, detectives spotted a man at the Burien Transit Center who appeared to be wearing the same clothes as the gunman seen in the video. Towle Leichliter, 46, was detained; detectives found a .40-caliber handgun in his backpack that was matched to a shell casing found at the shooting scene. The motive for the shooting is unknown. Leichliter was arrested and charged with second-degree murder.

Cortez and Juarez were hanging out with a large group of teens at the Alturas @ Burien apartment complex when they apparently got into an argument with a member of a rival gang. Both were shot multiple times. No arrests have been made. Cortez and Juarez are presumed victims of an ongoing war between rival Hispanic street gangs in South King County.

Scotland was strangled and then after her death was stabbed to make it appear part of a robbery. Aterraka Scotland, now 27, was arrested at a Redmond bus stop on April 4 and has been charged with second-degree murder domestic violence. According to prosecutors, Aterraka Scotland killed her wife after finding out she was having an affair.

Several people called 911 to report hearing gunshots and Seattle police found McKoy, a rapper who went by the moniker “Juice The God,” lying in the street with a gunshot wound to the head. No arrests have been made.

Witnesses at a hit-and-run told police a man and woman had fled their crashed vehicle into a residential neighborhood and attempted to steal a car. Officers arrested the woman, but the man broke into an unoccupied house and armed himself with a gun he found inside. After a nine-hour standoff, a SWAT team entered the house and found Nelson hiding in the crawl space. He fired at officers twice, then exchanged gunfire with a 39-year-old Federal Way police officer, who shot Nelson several times.

On April 13, Seattle police responded to a report of an unresponsive man inside a camper near the Ballard Bridge. Officers initially assumed Matteson had died of natural causes. During an autopsy, investigators discovered Matteson had been shot in the chest, triggering a homicide investigation. No arrests have been made.

Balesh got into a fight with a male relative at his father’s apartment and was stabbed to death. His relative, now 37, was arrested on investigation of homicide but was released from jail on April 19 and has not been criminally charged. According to prosecutors, evidence in the case suggests the relative killed Balesh in self-defense.

Baker, the older brother of Bishard “Budda” Baker, a former UW Husky football player who now plays in the NFL for the Arizona Cardinals, died on a Ballard street from a gunshot wound to the chest. Police say video-surveillance footage shows Robert Baker inside the Cedar Room, where he and Christopher Gates appeared to recognize each other. Gates is accused of following Baker from the club and shooting him. Gates, now 26, was charged with first-degree murder.

A wild shootout in the parking lot shared by the Skyway Veterans of Foreign Wars post and Tha Family Motorcycle Club ended with at least four people shot. Cabine died in the parking lot of a nearby McDonald’s restaurant. Justice was driven in a private vehicle to Valley Medical Center, where he died. Two others were shot but survived. No arrests have been made.

Cervantes Villanueva was among a group of young men who were hanging out at a female friend’s house until her mother told them to leave. He was waiting for a ride and sat in the front seat of a dilapidated BMW with a 14-year-old boy. The 14-year-old was taking selfies of himself with a 9 mm handgun when the weapon discharged, hitting Cervantes Villanueva. The shooter fled to Texas but was arrested July 8 in a traffic stop as he and his sister were on their way to their mother’s house in Kent. The shooter, who has since turned 15, was charged in juvenile court with first-degree manslaughter and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm. He pleaded guilty in January and was sentenced to 52 to 65 weeks.
Marr was shot multiple times in the parking lot at West Seattle Stadium and was declared dead at Harborview Medical Center. No arrests have been made.

During a gathering at a friend’s house, a 21-year-old man was mishandling his gun when it accidentally discharged. A round hit Glover in the neck and he died at the scene. The shooting was ruled accidental and no one was charged.

Manuel Ramirez Nava, who was 16 at the time, allegedly stole a .38-caliber handgun from his neighbor and was playing around with the weapon at a birthday party. Two witnesses reported seeing Ramirez cock the gun, which went off. A bullet struck Bingham in the head and he died at the scene. Ramirez was charged as an adult with first-degree manslaughter and second-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Dela Cruz and a group of friends were “ghost hunting” in Seattle’s Martha Washington Park when a group of suspected gang members pulled up in a car. The group in the car opened fire and Dela Cruz was shot three times. Dela Cruz, who had planned to join the Marines, was weeks from graduating from Franklin High School when he was killed. No arrests have been made.

Pecina was stabbed in the neck by another man in what police say was a targeted attack near Luna Park on the West Seattle waterfront. There have been no arrests. In January, Seattle police used evidence from Pecina’s killing to produce the department’s first video showcasing evidence from a homicide investigation and announced that detectives have the unidentified killer’s DNA.
Lafferty was shot in the chest, apparently by someone he knew following a fight. The shooter fled before police arrived. No one has been arrested.

Four Redmond police officers fired 13 rounds at Castellano at a gas station in Kirkland’s Kingsgate neighborhood, striking him at least four times. Castellano, who had a pending felony drug charge, was being investigated for eluding a police vehicle and nine counts of identity theft, according to a police spokeswoman. The police investigation into the shooting is still underway.

Arancio, a clerk at the America’s Best Value Airport Inn, was shot in the chest during a robbery in which $150 was taken. Daye’vion Royalston, 26, was arrested in Dayton, Ohio, five days later and was charged with first-degree murder and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Barreto was days from graduating from Mount Rainier High School when police say her boyfriend lured her to Salt Air Vista Park and shot her in the head. Giovanni “Gio” Herrin, now 20, was arrested June 19 and is charged with first-degree murder domestic violence and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm. In July, he escaped from Harborview Medical Center after faking a medical emergency. Herrin was shot in the shoulder by a jail officer a half-mile away and was taken back into custody.

Gutierrez, shot eight times, was found in the driver’s seat of his car in Shoreline. Nine hours later, Seattle police arrested a then-17-year-old, Luis Campuzano, for unlawful possession of a firearm. Police found a 9 mm handgun in Campuzano’s vehicle that was later matched to shell casings found at the homicide scene. Sheriff’s deputies obtained video footage that showed Campuzano getting into Gutierrez’s car and leaving a short time later with a backpack. The apparent motive for the killing was the alleged robbery of cocaine and cash. Campuzano, now 18, was charged as an adult with first-degree murder and unlawful possession of a firearm.
Seattle police responded to a report of a stabbing in Pioneer Square and found Roberts dead from a stab wound to the chest. There have been no arrests.

Dasalla and her boyfriend, Kenneth Thomas, were arguing in their bedroom when Dasalla texted her son, telling him he needed to leave the house. As the son left, he heard gunshots and called 911. Officers found Dasalla, dead from a gunshot wound to the neck, on the floor of her bedroom. Thomas, 48, was arrested and is charged with second-degree murder domestic violence.

Morales and a 32-year-old man were shot following a hip-hop concert at a music venue in Sodo. Police officers, who were already patrolling the area as a large crowd was leaving the concert, heard gunshots and discovered the victims. Morales died a short time later at Harborview Medical Center. The second victim was treated for non-life-threatening injuries. No arrests have been made.

When Landers and her husband didn’t show up at a Fourth of July party, a friend went to their house and called 911 after discovering Landers’ body. She died from multiple gunshot wounds. The body of her husband, Paul Landers, 51, was also inside the home. His death, from a handgun wound to the head, was ruled a suicide. Police are still awaiting lab results but the deaths were investigated as a murder-suicide.

Anderson and another friend were hanging out in the bedroom of Loren Mertes, 20, who was playing with a loaded shotgun. Mertes, who later claimed he didn’t know the gun was loaded, chambered a shell and pulled the trigger, striking Anderson in the chest. Mertes was charged with first-degree manslaughter.

Brown and another teenage friend were hanging out at the home of John Mugo, who was also 17 at the time. All three had guns and took a variety of photos of themselves with the weapons. Prosecutors say Mugo was playing around with his gun and shot Brown once in the head, then attempted to make it appear that Brown had shot himself. Mugo was charged as an adult with first-degree manslaughter and first-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.

Chikh and a male friend had gone for dinner and were leaving a shopping plaza when Chikh’s husband, Ignacio Cisneros, used his vehicle to block Chikh’s vehicle. He got out of his car and angrily confronted Chikh. Cisneros then returned to his vehicle, got a handgun and shot Chikh and her friend as they sat inside her Cadillac Escalade. Cisneros turned himself in to police five days later. He was charged with premeditated first-degree murder domestic violence and attempted first-degree murder.

Officers responded to a 911 report of a man down in the street and found Abay dead from numerous stab wounds. A few weeks after the homicide, police released video-surveillance footage of two men and two women associated with the stabbing in an effort to identify them. No arrests have been made.

Kent police responded to a report of gunshots outside a restaurant and witnesses pointed to a red pickup that drove from the scene without its headlights on. The driver, Emiliano Garcia, then 16, led police on a high-speed chase. Officer Mark Williams pursued the pickup and accidentally struck and killed Officer Moreno, who had just placed spike strips across the roadway. Garcia crashed the pickup a mile east; he and one of his passengers fled. The second passenger was arrested and charged in juvenile court with unlawfully possessing a gun and cocaine. The passenger who fled with Garcia was later charged with unlawful possession of a firearm. Garcia, who was arrested at his Kent residence later that day, was charged as an adult with second-degree murder. He remains jailed in lieu of $1 million bail.

A motel employee found Wu’s body in her room and called police. Based on video-surveillance footage, detectives identified Pvt. 2nd Class Krishna Mahadevan-Prasad, 20, of Woodridge, New Jersey, as a suspect. The Army Ranger had transferred to Joint Base Lewis-McCord two weeks earlier. Early the next day, Mahadevan-Prasad – who was armed with a shotgun and an assault-style rifle – fired at parked vehicles waiting for the Hood Canal Bridge to open. He then shot and killed himself.

King County sheriff’s Deputy Leland Adams was looking for parking violators in the garage at Kent Station. He came across a suspicious vehicle and was contacting two men when he was told over his police radio that the car had been reported stolen. Adams tried to arrest the driver, later identified as Hernandez. Hernandez armed himself with an AR-15 rifle and fought with the deputy. Adams fired a single shot, striking Hernandez in the chest. He died a short time later at Harborview Medical Center.

Witnesses told police they saw some kind of disturbance, then saw a car quickly driven off. They found a man’s body on the ground and called police. The victim, Kotthoff, died from a gunshot wound to the head. Police identified two men, who were 43 and 37 at the time, as being involved in Kotthoff’s death. Prosecutors declined to file criminal charges after determining the men acted in self-defense.

Someone called 911 to report that a man and a woman had been shot. Guerrero died at the scene and the female victim, who was shot in the leg, was treated at Harborview Medical Center. No arrests have been made but police do not think the shooting was random.

Fehlen and other passengers aboard a Metro bus were angry at a teenage rider who repeatedly pulled the stop cord. When Fehlen indicated he was getting off the bus, the teen left the bus before him. The teenager, later identified as 16-year-old Loyan Ahmed, fired at Fehlen, hitting him four times before running away. Police found Fehlen on the sidewalk next to the bus; he died a short time later at Harborview Medical Center. Police identified Ahmed through surveillance footage and he was arrested on Aug. 15. He was charged as an adult with second-degree murder and second-degree unlawful possession of a firearm.
